                <head>323. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>In briefing the National Security Council on September 18 on significant world
                    developments affecting U.S. security, Acting Director of Central Intelligence
                    General <persName corresp="#p_CGCP1">Charles P. Cabell</persName> offered the
                    following assessment of developments in Lebanon and Jordan: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Turning to the Middle East, General <persName corresp="#p_CGCP1"
                                >Cabell</persName> stated that while the security situation in
                            Lebanon had shown superficial signs of improvement, there was
                            nevertheless serious unrest among the pro-<persName corresp="#p_CC7"
                                >Chamoun</persName> elements of the population. The most critical
                            period, he predicted, would come after the inauguration of General
                                <persName corresp="#p_CGF2">Chehab</persName> next Wednesday.</p>
                        <p>“In Jordan, General <persName corresp="#p_CGCP1">Cabell</persName>
                            stated, United Nations Secretary General Hammarskjöld’s attempt to
                            implement the recent United Nations Resolution had failed.” (Memorandum
                            of discussion at the 379th meeting of the National Security Council,
                            prepared by Gleason; Eisenhower Library, <persName>Whitman</persName>
                            File, NSC Records)</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
            </div>
